<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="103" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1875,2046]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1875,1902]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kaszab, 1940" authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1940" box="[640,1141,1875,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi" subGenus="Platyscelis">
<emphasis box="[640,761,1875,1901]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Platyscelis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[781,902,1875,1901]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Platyscelis</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[922,972,1876,1902]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">freyi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kaszab, Z." box="[982,1141,1875,1902]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="119 - 235" refId="ref18574" refString="Kaszab, Z. (1940) Revision der Tenebrioniden-Tribus Platyscelini (Col. Teneb.). Mitteilungen der Munchener Entomologischen Gesellschaft, 30 (1), 119 - 235 + 896 - 1003, 3 pls." type="book chapter" year="1940">Kaszab, 1940</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from the latter by the following characters: (1) elytral surface with short thick setae (long in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1940" box="[1179,1256,1912,1938]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis box="[1179,1256,1912,1938]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">P. freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (2) metatibiae curved, wide and flat (straight and narrow in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1940" box="[659,736,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis box="[659,736,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">P. freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (3) parameres narrowing towards apex straightly, outer margins with long and sharp hooks at apex, apex curved to dorsal side in lateral view (arcuately, extremely weak, not curved in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1940" box="[263,341,2020,2046]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freyi">
<emphasis box="[263,341,2020,2046]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">P. freyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="106" pageId="3" pageNumber="104" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,647]" box="[199,672,152,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,152,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Description.</emphasis>
Body black, weakly shining.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,647]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,189,215]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[274,350,188,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[362,406,188,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–20" captionStartId="6.[154,267,1923,1948]" captionTargetBox="[195,1411,199,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[161,1421,161,1925]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 5–20. Parameres of male aedeagus in dorsal and lateral view. 5–6. Platyscelis acutipenis; 7–8. P. amdoensis; 9–10. P. angusticollis angusticollis; 11–12. P. angusticollis platytarsis; 13–14. P. bogatshevi; 15–16. P. brevis; 17–18. P. confusa;" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150816/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">5–6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[417,447,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–38" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1190,1215]" captionTargetBox="[180,1417,196,1121]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[161,1426,181,1130]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 37–38. Thick setae on elytral surface (under 5x of Canon MP-E 65 mm). 37. Platyscelis acutipenis; 38. P. freyi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150834/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[458,490,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–44" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1746,1771]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,204,1705]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[153,1438,179,1710]" captionText="FIGURES 39–44. Habitus. 39–40. Platyscelis acutipenis (39. male, holotype; 40. female, paratype); 41. P. amdoensis (male); 42–43. P. angusticollis angusticollis (males; 42. lectotype); 44. P. angusticollis platytarsis (male, lectotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3404777/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">39</figureCitation>
). Anterior margin of frontoclypeus straight, surface with dense and moderately coarse punctures. Frons and genae weakly convex, with punctures dense and coarse. Eyes transverse, anterior margin shallowly emarginate. Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[481,549,260,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: B) nearly reaching base of pronotum, 2nd to 8th antennomeres cylindrical and thicker at apex, 9th to 10th almost spherical, and 11th sharped-oval. Length (width) ratio of 2nd to 11th antennal segments 25 (19): 67 (21): 37 (22): 36 (20): 38 (20): 35 (21): 36 (26): 31 (27): 31 (27): 39 (27).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,647]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[324,391,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: A) transverse and convex, widest at base, 1.6 times as wide as long, 2.2 times as wide as head. Lateral margins arcuately narrowing toward apex. Ratio of width at anterior margin to basal 26: 50. Anterior margin nearly straight and posterior one sinuate. Anterior angles obtuse and posterior ones rectangular. Lateral margins edged in anterior margin and posterior one not edged, entire lateral margins edged, widely depressed from base to middle. Punctures fine and dense on disc but extremely dense and coarse, and merged partially at sides. Prothoracic hypomera with dense wrinkles, granule and sparse yellow setae. Prosternum before procoxae with yellow setae, prosternal process projecting beyond level of procoxae, sharp at apex in lateral view. Mesoventrite with punctures and yellow setae.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="104" startId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" targetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1842,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,391,1842,1867]" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">FIGURES 1–2. (A–K)</emphasis>
. Male characters. 1. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bai &amp; Ren" authorityYear="2019" box="[608,830,1842,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutipenis">
<emphasis box="[608,830,1842,1866]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">Platyscelis acutipenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 2. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Egorov" authorityYear="1989" box="[872,1005,1842,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Platyscelis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amdoensis">
<emphasis box="[872,1005,1842,1866]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="104">P. amdoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Elytra oval and weak convex, base moderately wider than pronotum and widest at middle, 1.1 times as long as wide and 1.2 times as wide as pronotum. Surface with short thick setae, traces of longitudinal carinae and sparse yellow soft setae, without punctures. Lateral carina nearly visible completely in dorsal view and almost reaching sutural angle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,719]" box="[199,1209,297,323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Abdomen with short sparse yellow setae, not depressed at middle of 1st and 2nd ventrites.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Profemora with sparse punctures and yellow setae. Protibiae (
<figureCitation box="[900,970,333,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: D) gradually widened towards apex and curved at inner side, underside concave at apex and apical margin foliate extended, inner side with dense yellow hairbrush at apex. Protarsi (
<figureCitation box="[466,536,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: C) moderately widened but narrower than apex of protibiae. Meso- and metafemora longer than profemora. Mesotibiae (
<figureCitation box="[654,725,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: E) gradually widened toward apex, with rufous strong setae. Mesotarsi (
<figureCitation box="[278,348,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: F) weakly widened and narrower than apex of mesotibiae. Metatibiae (
<figureCitation box="[1168,1238,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: G) curved, wide and flat, with rufous strong setae. Length (width) ratio of pro-, meso- and metafemora 26 (9): 28 (8): 34 (10), that of corresponding tibiae 25 (8): 26 (6): 37 (6), and protarsi 26 (27): 32 (49): 26 (42): 20 (24): 70 (24), mesotarsi 51 (30): 41 (38): 31 (30): 27 (24): 74 (22), metatarsi (
<figureCitation box="[716,784,585,611]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: H) 115 (30): 54 (29): 42 (26): 86 (27).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,153,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[326,405,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1842,1867]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,747,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[153,1438,702,1786]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. (A–K). Male characters. 1. Platyscelis acutipenis; 2. P. amdoensis; A. pronotum; B. antenna; C. protarsi; D. protibiae; E. mesotibiae; F. mesotarsi; G. metatibiae; H. metatarsi; I–K. aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view. Measuring scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150808/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
